configuration/preprocessors.md
     1→# Configuring Preprocessors
     2→
     3→Preprocessors are extensions that can modify the raw Markdown source before it gets sent to the renderer.
    26→## Custom preprocessor configuration
    27→
    28→Preprocessors can be added by including a `preprocessor` table in `book.toml` with the name of the preprocessor.
    29→For example, if you have a preprocessor called `mdbook-example`, then you can include it with:
    45→## Locking a preprocessor dependency to a renderer
    46→
    47→You can explicitly specify that a preprocessor should run for a renderer by
    48→binding the two together.
    55→## Provide your own command
    56→
    57→By default when you add a `[preprocessor.foo]` table to your `book.toml` file,
    58→`mdbook` will try to invoke the `mdbook-foo` executable. If you want to use a
    59→different program name or pass in command-line arguments, this behaviour can
    60→be overridden by adding a `command` field.
    67→### Optional preprocessors
    68→
    69→If you enable a preprocessor that isn't installed, the default behavior is to throw an error.
    70→This behavior can be changed by marking the preprocessor as optional:
    79→## Require a certain order
    80→
    81→The order in which preprocessors are run can be controlled with the `before` and `after` fields.
    82→For example, suppose you want your `linenos` preprocessor to process lines that may have been `{{#include}}`d; then you want it to run after the built-in `links` preprocessor, which you can require using either the `before` or `after` field:
